post_text: So proud of Big Lake Elementary heroes!
shared_text:
West Lakes Fire Department
September 4 at 4:26 PM ¬∑

Today West Lakes Fire Dept., along with Mat-Su Borough EMS, were honored to present Hero awards to two very brave and smart young ladies. Lily and Bella witnessed a man in medical distress and sprang into action, alerting adults at Big Lake Elementary that someone needed help and an ambulance. Staff from Big Lake Elementary quickly responded with an AED and called 911. Everyone involved helped using their unique skills.
Thank you Big Lake Elementary Grizzlies!
Lily and Bella you are our heroes!

post_text: www.covid19.alaska.gov
shared_text:
Alaska Health and Social Services
May 17 at 12:49 PM ¬∑

We recognize that many Alaskans are feeling lonely and could use more social support including help with child care. One choice Alaskans now have, thanks to everyone's hard work to flatten our curve, is to slightly expand your social bubble to be connected with a few close friends or another family to help support each other. Create a small and consistent "trusted bubble" and outside that bubble, keep up the great work staying at least 6 feet from others to keep case counts low in Alaska. Learn more: dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/bubble.aspx

Mat-Su Borough School District will have a regular School Board Meeting on Wednesday, May 6 at 6pm. To view the agenda and Live Stream link visit: https://go.boarddocs.com/ak/matsu/Board.nsf/Public

The Action Item to ‚ÄòRescind April 22, 2020 vote - High School English Elective Curriculum and Reading List Part I‚Äô is open to public testimony. For more information on how to provide testimony, see below. A motion to approve this agenda item would undo the entire approval of curriculum documents, including amended reading lists.

Due to State of Alaska Health Mandate 11 requirements, Mat-Su School Board meetings will be held telephonically and there will be no physical access to the building. Members of the public wishing to provide testimony telephonically must sign up no later than 3pm the day of the meeting by calling or emailing School Board Administrative Assistant: Stacy.Escobedo@matsuk12.us or 907-746-9272

SCHOOL IS OPEN this morning and buses will be trying to get to every location as normal. However, many roads have large drifts that will hinder traffic flow this morning. The following roads are closed and will not have bus service due to large drifts:
Scott Road in Palmer
Rider Road off of Palmer-Fishhook
Werner Road off of Palmer-Fishhook
Davis Road on Fairview Loop is sealed off at this time
Engstrom north of Zephyr

MSBSD Recommendations for pupil transportation:
If your student is waiting for a bus for more than 10 minutes this morning, the bus may not be able to access your section of the road and that student should return home. Absences for these students blocked from transportation to school will be excused. Please call your school's front office for support.

Please exercise caution when traveling this morning. Many roads around the valley have large drifts and low visibility. Message

post_text: Alaska State Troopers (Official) K9 Kimmik and Trooper Rallo visited Knik Elementary School yesterday!
shared_text:
Alaska State Troopers (Official)
February 24 at 6:32 PM ¬∑

Trooper Rallo introduced Kimmik to the kiddos at Knik Elementary school that came up with the K9s name. Kimmik is a three year old male Belgian Malinois. He is what we call a ‚Äúdual-purpose‚Äù canine, meaning he is trained to conduct patrol work and sniff out certain controlled substances. A student in the class came up with the name Kimmik because his grandparents had a dog by that name and it was a good dog. The class liked that it was an Inupiaq name and means ‚Äòdog‚Äô and that is why they suggested it for the new K9. The students were amazed at how attentive Kimmik is to Trooper Rallo and how well behaved he was. They especially loved it when Kimmik would find the hidden objects around the room and get his toy as a reward. AST would like to thank the Matanuska-Susitna Borough School District for sharing these great photos with us.
text:
Alaska State Troopers (Official) K9 Kimmik and Trooper Rallo visited Knik Elementary School yesterday!

Alaska State Troopers (Official)
February 24 at 6:32 PM ¬∑

Trooper Rallo introduced Kimmik to the kiddos at Knik Elementary school that came up with the K9s name. Kimmik is a three year old male Belgian Malinois. He is what we call a ‚Äúdual-purpose‚Äù canine, meaning he is trained to conduct patrol work and sniff out certain controlled substances. A student in the class came up with the name Kimmik because his grandparents had a dog by that name and it was a good dog. The class liked that it was an Inupiaq name and means ‚Äòdog‚Äô and that is why they suggested it for the new K9. The students were amazed at how attentive Kimmik is to Trooper Rallo and how well behaved he was. They especially loved it when Kimmik would find the hidden objects around the room and get his toy as a reward. AST would like to thank the Matanuska-Susitna Borough School District for sharing these great photos with us.

post_text: Mat-Su Career & Tech Ed High School Wins Science Bowl üéâüèÜ The Regional Science Bowl is a highly competitive science and academic event among teams of high school students who compete in a fast-paced verbal forum to solve technical problems and answer questions in all branches of science and math. Teams from Colony High, Career Tech High, Lathrop High, and Palmer High, battled it out Friday, February 7th, to qualify for a free trip to the Science Bowl Nationals in Washington D.C. Congratulations to Career Tech Team 1: Kira Fagerstrom, Tibor Huxford, Alex Prayner, Xander Backus, Kadin Bierman.

post_text:
Building strong and sustainable industry partnerships is key to CTE program success. Ravn Alaska presented students with welding helmets, coats, and gloves, and thanked them for their hard work on several RAVN Air Group projects they worked on. RAVN has also donated safety equipment and fuselages for use in our programs.

UA Local 367 Plumbers & Steamfitters donated industrial welders and metal to our Industrial programs and are excited to foster opportunities for our students to enter apprenticeships with the 367.

Both employers were beyond impressed and thankful for the work Matanuska-Susitna Borough School District CTE does in preparing our students for success. The importance of Employability Skills such as communication, punctuality, teamwork, and problem solving were emphasized by both employers as well as excitement for the future of high demand, high wage employment in the fields both these partners represent.
